The first quantity that we can study is the growth of the number R of removed/recovered sites as a function of time. As expected, all of our simulations are in the indefinite-growth regime (see for lower values of p, where R plateaus as the epidemic dies out). The behavior with time seems to approach a power law, but is difficult to analyze. We can, however, make use of the spatial nature of our model to find a more appropriate scaling variable. Indeed, a simple and intuitive spatial observable is the radius of gyration \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
